        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Configuration:
--------------
The CO source has been measured to be 1.6" extended in one direction (unresolved along its minor axis).  We request an angular resolution of 0.8arcsec as this will allow us to map the distribution of emission with about a SNR per beam, if the line is as bright as we predict (S DeltaV = 8 Jy km/s, this is a conservative estimate as we do not know how much of the star formation takes place in either of the two sources).

Sensitivity:
------------
[CII] LINE:  Using the relation between SFR and the [CII] luminosity, we require a sensitivity that would enable a detection of a L_[CII] = 2.5x10^9 Lsun.   The depth requested is set by the predicted line flux of the [CII] line at 494.16GHz, which is S DeltaV = 8 Jy km/s.  We request a sensitivity of 2.0 mJy/beam/100kms.  This would result in a SNR of 10 at the peak of the line if the source would be a point source.  However, the emission is expected to be extended over at least two beams.
CONTINUUM:  The continuum emission is predicted to be 45 mJy at 495GHz.  If all the emission arise from only one source (the quasar or the companion starburst), then the SNR will be high.  However, as we aim to measure if the continuum emission originates from both sources, it is important we have deep observations.  At the sensitivity of 0.3 mJy, we would be able to detect a far-infrared luminosity of 2x10^11 Lsun (assuming a modified blackbody with T=30K and beta=1.5).  This limit is essential to be able to discriminate between star formation in the quasar host and the companion starburst.
We note that the overhead time is 32% of the total time. The estimated time will allow us to reach the desired sensitivity. The overheads estimated from the OT are standard.

Correlator setup:
-----------------
We request a spectral setup with one baseband tuned to the redshift [CII] line (at frequency = 494.16GHz), which we expect has a line width of 400 km/s. For this baseband we select the widest possible band of 1.875GHz.  We include a spectral averaging of 16 channels in order to reduce the data rate (the resulting spectral resolution of 4.7 km/s is sufficient for the expected broad line). 
The other three basebands are set as continuum with the 2GHz wide bands.  No lines are expected.
</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
