    <prp:code/>
    <prp:abstract>The correlation between the central super-massive black hole mass and the mass of the bulge is well-known, although we still do not have knowledge about the origin of this correlation. Studies of high-z quasars bring insight to the SMBH growth alongside the growth of the host galaxy's stellar mass.  
We here propose to do ALMA observations of SMMJ04135+10277, which is a z=2.84 quasar discovered as a submm-bright source. However, a very massive CO molecular gas reservoir was found in a nearby companion galaxy, not the quasar. This suggests that the quasar is gas-poor, and therefore this system could be a wet-dry merger. Our aims are:
(1) determine how large a fraction of the mm continuum emission arise from the QSO and the companion galaxy, resp., in order to constrain each of their star formation rates, and determine if there is a starburst in the host galaxy;
(2) determine the star formation rate of the quasar host galaxy and the companion galaxy using the [CII] emission line and to investigate whether the quasar host is starburst powered or AGN dominated;
(3) determine the excitation properties of the molecular gas and if these are similar to that of SMGs or of mm-bright QSOs. </prp:abstract>
